PUH-BrianMartell magnetism can be focused, but not exactly like light through a glass lens (refraction). Magnetic fields are divergence-free (∇·B = 0), so they form closed loops and cannot be “bent” the same way. Instead, we channel and compress them using materials or geometries that guide flux lines. Understandable explanation: •  Light focusing: Photons bend via refractive index change (Snell’s law). •  Magnetic focusing: Flux seeks path of least reluctance (analogous to resistance). High-permeability materials (μ >> 1, e.g., iron, Mu-metal) act as “flux conduits” — lines crowd into the material, compressing density B at the tip or gap. •  Common methods: 	•  Passive: Ferromagnetic cones/poles concentrate field (Halbach arrays, magnetic lenses). 	•  Active: Electromagnets (quadrupoles, solenoids) in particle accelerators focus charged beams. 	•  Advanced: Metamaterials create negative μ for sub-diffraction focusing (research stage).
